</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="653" pageNumber="654" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="653" pageNumber="654">
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Geopinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="653" pageNumber="654" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Geopinus</taxonomicName>
LeConte, 1847: 371. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1829" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Daptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="653" pageNumber="654" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incrassatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="653" pageNumber="654">Daptus incrassatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1829 by monotypy. Etymology. From the Greek prefix 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="653" pageNumber="654">geo-</emphasis>
(earth) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="653" pageNumber="654">pinos</emphasis>
(dirt, filth), probably alluding to the habitat where LeConte found his specimens (&quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="653" pageNumber="654">terram laborans, quasi fodiens</emphasis>
&quot;) [masculine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="653" pageNumber="654" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="653" pageNumber="654">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="653" pageNumber="654">One North American species in the temperate regions.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
